## Migration & Brain Drain Statistics

### Migration Trends (2010-2025)

| Year | Net Migration | Trend | Key Factors |
|---|---|---|---|
| **2019** | -94,900 | High outflow | Economic instability |
| **2020** | -92,400 | Continued outflow | COVID-19 impact |
| **2021** | -92,400 | Stable outflow | Economic crisis deepening |
| **2022** | -77,495 | Slight improvement | 16.13% decline from 2021 |
| **2023-2025** | Ongoing | Brain drain continues | IT professionals migrating |

### Brain Drain Impact on IT Sector

| Factor | Impact | Statistics |
|---|---|---|
| **Engineering Migration to Australia** | High | 70.1% cite low salaries as motivation |
| **Sri Lanka Brain Drain Ranking** | Global: 20th | South Asia: 9th position |
| **Brain Drain Index** | 7.6 points | 2023 measurement |
| **Primary Destinations** | Australia, Middle East, Europe | IT professionals leading exodus |

## Employment Market Analysis

### Job Market Trends (2023-2025)

| Metric | Current Status | Trend |
|---|---|---|
| **Active Job Postings** | Fluctuating | +1.13% month-over-month, -3.89% year-over-year |
| **Employment Rate** | 95.90% | Q3 2024 (up from 95.30% in Q2) |
| **University Graduate Employment** | Challenging | High unemployment among educated youth |
| **Private Sector Premium** | 66-128% higher | Compared to A-level holders |

## Campus Recruitment & Graduate Statistics

### University Graduate Employment

| Category | Statistics | Details |
|---|---|---|
| **Private Sector Employment** | 23% of graduates | Significantly higher salaries |
| **Government Sector** | 77% of graduates | Lower but stable employment |
| **Age Groups Most Affected** | 20-24 and 25-29 years | Highest unemployment rates |
| **Historical Unemployment Trend** | Declining | From 15.9% (1990) to 5.2% (2008) |

