## Regional Employment Distribution

### Major IT Employment Areas

| Region | Employment Concentration | Salary Premium |
|---|---|---|
| **Colombo** | Highest | 20-30% above national average |
| **Kandy** | Growing hub | 10-15% above national average |
| **Galle** | Emerging | 5-10% above national average |
| **Remote Work** | Increasing | International rates ($20,000-$50,000) |

## Migration Destination Analysis (IT Professionals)

| Destination | Popularity | Average Salary Increase | Visa Requirements |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Australia** | Very High | 500-800% | Skilled migration visa |
| **Canada** | High | 400-600% | Express Entry system |
| **Middle East (UAE/Qatar)** | High | 300-500% | Sponsorship required |
| **Singapore** | Medium | 400-700% | Employment pass |
| **Europe (Germany/Netherlands)** | Growing | 600-1000% | Blue card/work permit |

## Key Insights and Recommendations

### Market Challenges
- **Significant salary gaps** between local and international markets
- **High brain drain** affecting skilled IT professionals
- **Limited career progression** opportunities locally
- **Economic instability** driving emigration

### Opportunities
- **Remote work growth** enabling international salary access
- **Government initiatives** to retain talent
- **Growing startup ecosystem** creating new opportunities
- **Digital transformation** increasing demand for IT skills

### Future Projections (2025-2027)
- Continued emigration of skilled IT professionals
- Increasing demand for remote work capabilities
- Growing importance of specialized skills (AI, Cloud, Cybersecurity)
- Potential government interventions to address brain drain

---

*Data compiled from PayScale, Salary.lk, Arc.dev, Levels.fyi, and various research studies on Sri Lankan migration patterns and employment statistics. Figures are estimates based on available data and market trends.*



